<TEXT>
a key issue at the 13th congress of the 
governing natonalist party is how to shift political power from the 
old guard conservatives to a new breed of progressive young leader 
if that sounds familiar it is because the partys archrival 
the communist party of mainland china grappled with exactly the 
same question at its own 13th congress in october 
the communists in china last year eased out of power most of the 
aging leaders who fought alongside mao tsetung to defeat the 
nationalists in a civil war that ended in 1949 
nationalist leader chiang kaishek fled to taiwan with about 2 
million followers to set up a government in exile and many of 
those former mainlanders remain at the center of power on this 
island of nearly 20 million 
many old guard nationalist leaders have announced plans to step 
down at the congress but the final lineup remains unclear and is 
the subject of intense speculation on taiwan 
ironically new blood is needed in both china and taiwan to 
follow through with sweeping reforms made by aging leaders from an 
earlier generation 
in china pragamatist deng xiaoping boldly decided that opening 
up to the outside world and introducing marketoriented economic 
reforms was needed to rebuild his country after the ruinous 196676 
cultural revolution 
for his policy to succeed however deng needed to replace his 
conservative contemporaries with a younger generation that was more 
enthusiastic about improving the economy than about marxist 
ideology 
he triumphantly engineered the changing of the guard at the 
october meeting taking with him into retirement a host of 
conservatives who served on the central committee and politburo 
since the meeting chinese communist party leader zhao ziyang 
has continued to seek rapid change of the economic system and now 
is concentrating on marketoriented price reform a controversial 
move that has fueled inflation 
in taiwan the economy had been robust but the political system 
needed an overhaul to avoid serious confrontation with an 
increasingly restive population 
ailing president chiang chingkuo the son of chiang kaishek 
decided to start loosening his partys authoritarian which for 
nearly 40 years tolerated little dissent 
before he died of heart failure in january chiang lifted 38 
years of martial law allowed formation of opposition parties 
scrapped a ban on new newspapers and eased restrictions on travel 
to china to allow family reunions 
he also promised to change taiwans parliamentary system which 
ensures a majority of seats are held by aging nationalists who 
arrived from mainland china with chiang kaishek in 1949 
chiangs successor president lee tenghui has vowed repeatedly 
to continue the political liberalization program 
on sunday he proposed that half the nationalist partys central 
committee step down to make room for younger members and more 
native taiwanese 
lee also wants to reform the statedominated financial system 
and tackle other thorny problems that have largely been neglected 
such as pollution and social security 
lee undoubtedly wants likeminded nationalist members to replace 
the conservatives who still dominate the top levels of party and 
government 
lees task is not as easy as dengs however he is still 
forming a power base and chiang is not around to use his 
unquestioned leadership to convince aging comrades the time for 
change has arrived 
local media reported in june that as many as half of the 
policymaking central standing committee planned to step down but 
in past days some newspapers predicted the turnover would not be 
that great 
premier yu kuohwa 74 widely viewed as the leader of the 
conservative faction was under pressure from younger party members 
to step down 
still there seemed to be little doubt that many of the 
septuagenarians and octogenarians holding top party posts would 
retire and the cabinet overhauled the congress concludes on 
thursday 
lees task will be to make sure enough new blood flows through 
the party and government to proceed with the liberalization 
policies initiated by chiang at a pace brisk enough to keep the 
taiwanese people satisfied 
