<TEXT>
the days of a man arriving home and 
having his wife waiting with a homecooked meal went out with 
leave it to beaver says anne reznikoff who is exploiting the 
situation by selling takehome meals to homebound commuters during 
evening rush hours 
reznikoff a new york marketing consultant uses a refrigerated 
van as her base at the stamford train station for selling fresh 
entrees that can be heated up in a microwave or conventional oven 
the business called hi honey im home offers a choice of 
three entrees nightly and has a total menu of 30 entrees ranging 
from grilled salmon steak with vegetables to meat loaf with mashed 
potatoes 
her target consumers are the thousands of metropolitan new york 
commuters who pass through the station daily 
reznikoff says boredom with the typical takeout staples of pizza 
and chinese food helped inspire creation of the business 
my husband and i would get home at 830 pm open the door 
and jokingly say hi honey im home reznikoff said but 
instead of smelling a tasty dinner in the oven wed find an old 
apple and a beer in the refrigerator 
so wed call out for pizza but theres only so much you can 
take of that she said 
reznikoffs diners have a choice of main dishes side dishes 
such as rice pilaf cornbread or stirfried vegetables and salads 
complete meals range in price from 7 to 9 
the truck is parked at the stamford train station from 4 pm to 
830 pm monday through friday to catch commuters coming home 
from new york and those leaving stamford offices to head into the 
city the company also delivers meals to offices in stamford 
leftovers are donated to a stamford shelter for troubled youths 
reznikoff said the business began operating about four weeks 
ago but she has been researching and planning it for a year 
research included the surveying of more than 1000 train commuters 
about their eating habits 
we found there are very few people who dont eat out at least 
once a week she said and people dont want complicated food 
they want meat loaf and mashed potatoes 
reznikoff and her husband stan bratskeir chairman of rand 
public relations inc in new york city are the owners they employ 
an operations manager and a vendor 
the meals are cooked by a kitchen staff of six in norwalk that 
is under contract to hi honey im home and other food services 
reznikoff described reaction to the truck so far as 
astounding 
we have people coming off the train calling their spouse and 
saying here is what they have tonight she said 
reznikoff said that during her first weeks in business the truck 
was selling a maximum of 60 dinners per night it is equipped to 
serve up to 300 dinners nightly she said 
reznikoff plans to open a truck at the greenwich train station 
by midsummer she eventually wants to have 30 trucks around the 
new york metropolitan region and she plans to start a lunch 
service 
there are two kinds of food reznikoff said theres 
homemade that takes a lot of time and is very good and food that 
is takeout that is convenient but not as satisfying 
our mission was to combine both and have convenient food that 
tastes homemade 
